AnnualHoursWorked = 10.145 + 110.230 Edu + (-1.581) \(Edu^2\)

  1. A one year increase in education would increase annual hour worked by 110.230 + (-1.581) [(educ+1)^2 - educ^2]

  2. 110.230 + (-1.581) * (17^2 - 16^2) = 58.057

  3. The relationship gets less positive as educ^2 will increase more fast as education gets larger.

  4. As Educ^3, educ^4 are inter-correlated to educ and educ^2

I think there is heteroskedasticity because for the first model, the residual changes as temperature increases. Besides, standard error of coefficient of temperature in robust is 0.01153, in first model is 0.01052, which means there is some heteroskedasticity error that was adjusted by the robust model.

5

For humidity, when temperature increases from -20 to 0. residual deacrease rapidly, while it keeps relatively less fluctuated around 0 when temperature increases from 0 to 30. So the effect of temperature on humidity is non-linear.
